FX  - I thank the anonymous reviewers, Andrew Kent, and Alex Loftus, for their extremely careful readings, and detailed and helpful suggestions to improve the paper, including references to additional historical material. For their generosity, constructive suggestions, and important critiques of versions of this paper I am indebted to: David Gilmartin, Donald Moore, Sarah Vaughn, Andrea Ballestero, Emma Shaw Crane, Shakirah E. Hudani, Lana Suleiman, Zahra Hayat, Saad Gulzar, and Akhtar Hayat. Navigating the policy documents would have been hard and dull without Audrey Thill. Research from which this paper draws was funded by the American Institute of Pakistan Studies, and the Nicholson Center at the University of Chicago. I had opportunities to present this paper at multiple fora, and benefitted from many people's generous engagement-for this I am grateful to the writing workshop convened at IAS by Didier Fassin, and the South Asia group meeting at the University of Notre Dame. I am also thankful to people at the British Library and the Irrigation Research Institute Library of the Punjab Irrigation Department who helped me navigate historical records. I have decided not to name the many people at the Irrigation Department with whom I have worked and from whom I have learnt so much in this past decade. But I make one exception: Mahmud-ul-Hasan Siddiqui, aka, Siddiqui sahib who passed away in April 2023. Siddiqui sahib was the first person whose office I was welcomed into in 2015, and a teacher and mentor since. This article is dedicated to Siddiqui sahib.
