AB  - Water-saving irrigation (WSI) can alleviate water scarcity and safeguard grain production, however, its promotion is hindered, and farmer participation remains low. This study aims to enhance farmer engagement in promoting WSI through policy intervention. Based on Technology Acceptance Model, interview data from 746 farmers in 2024, Ordered Logit and PLS-SEM models were employed to compare the relationships of the pathways of policy evaluation (PE), WSI perception, and perceived self-competence (PSC) on the adoption-publicitypay intention (INT) of non-adopted and adopted stage farmers. The results indicate that the average payment for WSI among farmers is 2529 CNY/ha/year, which covers approximately half of the total WSI cost. PE is associated with INT directly and indirectly through the intermediary WSI perception and PSC, while WSI perception and PSC are also directly associated with INT. The association between PE and INT varies across non-adopted and adopted stage farmers, with non-adopters being more sensitive to PE. Therefore, the government should prioritize support for non-adopters. Secondary promotional incentives and cost-sharing measures may be implemented for current adopters to expand the WSI promotion fund. This study fills a gap in understanding the mechanism by which PE is associated with INT at different adoption stages and provides theoretical and practical insights into the large-scale diffusion of WSI for policymakers, agricultural extension agencies, and researchers.
