TI  - Examining a national agricultural extension and advisory system: A case study of the North West and South West regions of Cameroon
T2  - ASIA LIFE SCIENCES
LA  - English
KW  - agricultural development
KW  - extension and advisory services
KW  - NGO
KW  - sustainable development
KW  - information and communication technology
KW  - SWOT analysis
KW  - Cameroon
AB  - Increasing needs for food safety and security, farm incomes, environmental conservation, and rural development demand relevant and efficient agricultural extension and advisory systems. Using a case design, this study analyzed strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats within an on-going national extension program and questioned how organizational functions influence form, policy, and practice in two regions in Cameroon. Four focus groups and 28 individual interviews provided data from 59 participants in stakeholder groups of farmer-leaders, NGOs, extension representatives and governmental counterparts. Eighteen themes emerged. Education, productivity, and decentralized structures were organizational strengths. Communication and feedback, insufficient human resource (HR) development, and organizational management were weaknesses. Opportunities included engaging producer organizations, exploiting natural and human resources, enabling environments, market development, and value-added processing. Climate change, conflict and corruption, diseases, governance, ICT, and program sustainability were threats. Six themes, i.e. collaboration and linkages, infrastructure development, ICT, conflict and corruption, program sustainability, and governance and policy, emerged in two or more SWOT categories. Finally, stakeholder priorities included: (1) providing an autonomous extension service that coordinates all advisory programs while collaborating among research and private advisory services; (2) implementing holistic policies that integrate health, innovations, markets, technology transfer, and value-chains to benefit all farmers; (3) redesigning subsidies and equitably incentivizing production and environmental practices; (4) increasing in-service staff training; and (5) disseminating innovations and harmonizing program activities. These findings underscore changes in a national agricultural extension service to improve organizational structures, relevance, and effectiveness, thus increasing the potential for meeting the needs of low and lower-middle economies.
