AB  - As a meso-level hub connecting macro-level policies and micro-level household behaviors, the degree of village organization reflects a village's structural integrity and the stability of its governance system. It helps overcome the constraints of structurally limited disaster prevention strategies among farmers, such as those caused by resource scarcity or information asymmetries. This research uses a social cognitive theory framework to analyze survey data encompassing 685 households across 54 flood-threatened villages in Sichuan Province, China. Through the Oprobit model and the mediation effect model, we systematically assess how village-level organizational development shapes farmers' disaster adaptation strategies while unpacking the latent transmission pathways. The results show that: (1) The degree of village organization is significantly negatively correlated with the flood adaptation behaviors of farmers. (2) There is an emotional crowdout effect and a risk perception passivation effect between the degree of village organization and farmers' flood adaptation behaviors. It is manifested that the degree of village organization will reduce farmers' local attachment and risk perception, thereby reducing their flood adaptation behavior. (3) The influence of the village organization degree on farmers' flood adaptation behaviors varies across different regions and income groups. The degree of village organization in non-plain areas and low-income groups is significantly negatively correlated with their flood adaptation behaviors. The findings make an effort to offer a philosophical perspective and empirical basis for enhancing the disaster prevention capacity in rural areas from the perspective of "village-farmer" collaboration.
