AB  - Salinity intrusion into coastal areas is a pervasive problem. Perceptions of effectiveness of adaptation strategies, and the factors influencing their adoption have been understudied. This study sets out to assess the effectiveness of adaptation strategies through the perceptions of coastal communities, in three unions of Bangladesh. Data were collected from randomly selected 400 households in Tiakhali, Patharghata, and Nishanbaria unions, which represent high-and moderate-salinity areas. Adjusted planting schedule, crop diversification, construction of embankments, salt-tolerant crop varieties, raising seed beds, bringing non-saline water through canals are highly effective in all areas. The marginal effects indicate that being in Tiakhali (high-salinity area) raises the probability of adopting salt-tolerant crop varieties, income diversification, and water treatment plants by 26.9%, 16.0%, and 29.2% points, respectively, compared to Nishanbaria (Moderate-salinity area). Similarly, being in Patharghata (high-salinity area) positively influences rooftop catchment systems, while negatively affecting tube well installation, raising seed beds. The findings highlight a critical role of zone-specific policies, aligned with local needs, as well as improved infrastructure. To enhance agricultural sustainability in the coastal regions across the country, an integrated water management plan is essential. Understanding these insights can provide policy makers with strong evidence to inform effective interventions and promote resilient livelihoods.
