AB  - CONTEXT: Maize is a critical component of the high-yield wheat-maize system in the North China Plain. Reducing the maize yield gap-the difference between actual and potential yields at the farm level-has wide implications for regional food security and agricultural policy.
   OBJECTIVE: In this paper, we combine farm-level survey data from Qihe County with the Hybrid-Maize crop model and stochastic frontier analysis to decompose this yield gap and highlight targeted policy solutions.
   KEY FINDINGS: Our analysis suggests that suboptimal management efficiency and inefficient input use make up the largest components of the yield gap, while technology adoption also presents a significant constraint. Notably, we observed divergent inter-annual trends: Core Area yields declined by 6.9% from 2023 to 2024 due to unfavorable weather conditions, whereas Radiation Area yields increased by 5.6%, reflecting successful technology diffusion. Another key finding is that planting density and fertilizer application consistently emerge as the most critical levers for yield improvement across different production zones. S
   IGNIFICANCE: Combining agronomic and socio-economic approaches is useful to identify potential intervention directions for sustainable intensification, though the specific policy recommendations derived from these observational findings require validation through pilot programs before contributing to county-wide production goals. (a target of 22.5 Mg ha(-1) combined yield for wheat-maize rotation systems).
