AB  - The agroclimatic zoning (AZ) approach is considered as an important tool to identify suitable areas for crops based on climate and soil data. AZ can improve passion fruit production and mitigate climate-related risks faced by farmers. This study focuses on Huila region- Colombia, aiming to characterize soil properties, map climatic variables, and create an AZ. Climate data and soil characteristics from legacy soil survey were used. The Agricultural Reference Index for Drought (ARID) was used to assess water deficit, while water excess was calculated through water balance. Spatial Multicriteria Evaluation (SMCE) determined the suitability of areas for cultivation, incorporating solar radiation, water deficit and excess, and soil properties. The current study identified three modeling scenarios (wet, normal, and dry) based on sowing dates. The results indicated that the landscape was dominated by well-drained and deeper soils. The northern subregion showed significant water deficits, while the southern subregion frequently experienced excess moisture. Solar radiation analysis indicated that areas with >= 7 h of sunlight varied significantly, with the northern subregion showing higher values. The SMCE highlighted the central and western regions as the most suitable areas for crop production due to favorable soil and drainage conditions. The integration of climate and soil data revealed that the southern region, despite its suitability, faces challenges with excess moisture, while the northern region's suitability is hampered by water stress. AZ will support informed decision-making of passion fruit farmers and create strategies to combat climate-related risks and ensure crop productivity.Graphical AbstractA new agroclimatic framework was designed to support decision-making for yellow passion fruit production areas. This framework was conducted in the Huila department, located in the southern part of Colombia, where passion fruit crops are prevalent. The agroclimatic zoning (AZ) process analyzed the soil-plant-atmosphere relationship, using legacy data, and a Spatial Multicriteria Evaluation (SMCE) approach. AZ output maps were not conceived as a static outcome but rather as a dynamic tool incorporating multiple scenarios, based on precipitation patterns variability (1985-2018). Three different water conditions scenarios were identified: normal, dry, and wet. Furthermore, water balance, water deficit, solar radiation, and soil properties information using SMCE were used as input data. As a result, several maps were generated rather than a single static result as illustrated in the graphical abstract. By identifying regional differences within the study area under varying climate scenarios, a set of targeted recommendations was then proposed, and presented in the bottom of the graphical abstract. These involved irrigation strategies to mitigate water stress in the northern region, and drainage management to address excess water in the south. The integrated framework ultimately aims to enhance decision-making by considering both agroclimatic potential and associated risks.
